export function getStaticPaths() {
  return [
    {
      params: { slug: 'feeding-guide' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'The Complete Rabbit Feeding Guide',
          category: 'Feeding',
          readTime: '5 min read',
          emoji: '🥕',
          content: `
## The golden rule: 80% hay

Hay should make up the vast majority of your rabbit's diet — around 80%. It keeps their digestive system moving and wears down their ever-growing teeth naturally. Timothy hay is ideal for adult rabbits. Meadow hay and orchard grass are good alternatives.

Never let your rabbit run out of hay. It should be available 24/7.

## Pellets: less is more

Pellets should only be a small part of the diet — around one egg cup per kilogram of body weight per day. Too many pellets lead to obesity and dental problems.

Choose plain pellets with no added seeds, nuts, or dried fruit (these are treats, not staples).

## Fresh vegetables

A small handful of fresh greens daily is ideal. Good choices include:
- Romaine lettuce (not iceberg — too watery)
- Fresh herbs: basil, parsley, coriander, dill
- Kale (in moderation)
- Broccoli leaves
- Carrot tops (the green leafy part, not loads of carrot)

Introduce new vegetables slowly and one at a time. Watch for soft stools — a sign something doesn't suit them.

## What to avoid

These are genuinely toxic to rabbits and must be kept away from them:
- **Avocado** — highly toxic
- **Onions and garlic** — can cause blood disorders
- **Rhubarb** — toxic
- **Potato and tomato leaves** — toxic
- **Apple seeds** — contain cyanide compounds
- **Iceberg lettuce** — causes diarrhoea in large amounts

## Water

Fresh water available at all times. A water bottle is more hygienic than a bowl, as rabbits can tip bowls and contaminate them. Change the water daily.

## Treats

Fruit is a treat, not a daily food. A small slice of apple (no seeds), a strawberry, or a piece of banana once or twice a week is plenty.

Commercial "rabbit treats" sold in pet shops are usually high in sugar and not recommended.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: 'first-time-owners' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'First-Time Rabbit Owner Guide',
          category: 'First-time owners',
          readTime: '8 min read',
          emoji: '🐣',
          content: `
## What to expect in the first few days

Your new rabbit will be nervous. This is completely normal. Give them time to explore at their own pace — don't try to pick them up constantly in the first 48 hours.

Set up their space before they arrive: hay, water, hiding spot, litter tray. Let them come out of their carrier in their own time.

## The handling learning curve

Most rabbits don't love being picked up — they're prey animals and being lifted off the ground triggers their flight instinct. With time and patience, most rabbits become very comfortable being handled.

Sit on the floor and let them come to you. Offer a piece of leafy greens from your hand. This builds trust faster than any amount of picking up.

## Litter training

Rabbits are naturally clean and surprisingly easy to litter train. Put a litter tray in the corner they naturally gravitate towards (usually a corner of their enclosure). Put some of their droppings in the tray to signal its purpose.

Use paper-based litter rather than clay or clumping cat litter. Add a layer of hay on top — rabbits like to eat hay and toilet at the same time.

## Signs your rabbit is happy

- Binkying: random leaping and twisting mid-air — pure joy
- Flopping: dramatically throwing themselves onto their side — very relaxed
- Tooth purring: gentle grinding sound when being stroked — content
- Approaching you: choosing to come close means they trust you

## Common mistakes

**Giving too much fruit and veg too soon.** Introduce changes to their diet slowly. A sudden change causes digestive upset.

**Not providing enough hay.** Dental problems are the number one rabbit health issue in the UK, almost always linked to insufficient hay.

**Getting a single rabbit.** Rabbits are highly social and most thrive with a companion. If you're only getting one, you'll need to provide a lot of interaction yourself.

**Underestimating space needs.** The minimum enclosure for one rabbit is much larger than most pet shop cages suggest. A hutch plus a permanent run is the minimum — free roaming in a rabbit-proofed room is ideal.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: 'housing-guide' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'Housing Your Rabbit: Indoor vs Outdoor',
          category: 'Housing',
          readTime: '6 min read',
          emoji: '🏠',
          content: `
## Minimum space requirements

The RWAF (Rabbit Welfare Association & Fund) recommends a minimum of 3m x 2m x 1m total space for two rabbits. This is far more than most pet shop hutches provide. A hutch should be thought of as a bedroom — not the entire living space.

A good setup is a large hutch permanently attached to or opening into a secure run.

## Indoor vs outdoor

**Indoor rabbits** tend to be more sociable and easier to bond with. They're also safer from predators, temperature extremes, and can receive more daily interaction. The downside is rabbit-proofing — they will chew cables and furniture if given the chance.

**Outdoor rabbits** need extra protection from foxes and other predators (padlocks, secure mesh, no gaps at ground level), and must have shelter from direct sun and rain. In winter, hutches need insulating and moving to a sheltered position.

## Bedding

Paper-based bedding (like Carefresh or Yesterday's News) is the best choice for the hutch floor. Avoid:
- Wood shavings or sawdust (respiratory irritant)
- Cedar or pine shavings (toxic oils)
- Straw as bedding (fine as hay, but uncomfortable as bedding and can scratch eyes)

Hay doubles as bedding and food and is ideal in the sleeping area.

## Cleaning

Spot-clean the litter tray daily. Full clean weekly — remove all bedding, disinfect with a pet-safe cleaner (F10 is excellent), allow to dry fully before adding fresh bedding.

## Temperature

Rabbits struggle in heat. Above 25°C becomes dangerous — keep outdoor rabbits in shade and provide frozen water bottles to lie against in summer. In winter, outdoor hutches should be insulated (old carpet on the roof and sides, not blocking ventilation) and moved to a garage or outbuilding if temperatures drop below freezing.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: 'bonding-rabbits' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'Bonding Two Rabbits Together',
          category: 'Bonding',
          readTime: '7 min read',
          emoji: '💛',
          content: `
## Why bond rabbits?

Rabbits are highly social animals and most are much happier with a companion. A bonded pair will groom each other, sleep together, and provide the constant company a rabbit needs. Single rabbits require far more human interaction to compensate.

## Before you start

Both rabbits should be neutered before bonding. Unneutered rabbits are driven by hormones that make bonding almost impossible — and two unneutered rabbits of any sex combination will fight.

Allow at least 6 weeks after neutering before attempting introductions.

## The bonding process

**Phase 1: Scent swapping (1–2 weeks)**
Swap bedding between the two rabbits' enclosures. Let them smell each other before they meet. No visual contact yet.

**Phase 2: Stress bonding (optional but effective)**
A short, mildly stressful experience together (like a car journey) can accelerate bonding. The shared experience makes them seek comfort in each other.

**Phase 3: Neutral territory meetings (days to weeks)**
Meet on completely neutral ground — somewhere neither rabbit has been. A bathroom, an empty room, even a car boot.

Watch for:
- ✅ Grooming each other — excellent sign
- ✅ Eating side by side — good sign
- ✅ Lying near each other — positive
- ⚠️ Chasing — monitor but don't always intervene
- 🛑 Biting, fur pulling, squealing — separate immediately

Gradually extend meeting times. Only move to a shared permanent space when they're consistently calm together.

## Setbacks are normal

Most bonds aren't linear. Two steps forward, one step back is typical. Patience is the key ingredient.

If you're struggling, feel free to ask us — we've bonded many pairs and are happy to advise.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: 'rabbit-health-basics' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'Rabbit Health: Signs to Watch For',
          category: 'Health',
          readTime: '5 min read',
          emoji: '🩺',
          content: `
## Know your rabbit's normal

The most important thing in rabbit health is knowing your individual rabbit. Learn their normal eating habits, droppings, and activity level — so you notice quickly when something changes.

## Red flags — contact a vet same day

- **Not eating or drinking** for more than a few hours
- **No droppings** — GI stasis is a genuine emergency in rabbits
- **Head tilt** — could indicate ear infection or neurological issue
- **Laboured breathing or open-mouth breathing**
- **Sudden lethargy or inability to move**
- **Seizures**

Rabbits deteriorate fast. Don't wait and see with any of the above.

## Common conditions

**GI Stasis** — the digestive system slows or stops. Usually caused by stress, insufficient hay, or pain. Signs: reduced or no droppings, hunched posture, not eating. Emergency — see a vet immediately.

**Dental disease** — overgrown teeth and spurs on molars. Caused by insufficient hay. Signs: drooling, dropping food, weight loss. Requires vet treatment (tooth filing under anaesthetic).

**E. cuniculi** — a parasitic infection that causes neurological symptoms including head tilt. Treatable if caught early.

**Snuffles** — bacterial upper respiratory infection. Signs: sneezing, nasal discharge. Treatable with antibiotics.

## Vaccinations

UK rabbits should be vaccinated annually against:
- Rabbit Viral Haemorrhagic Disease (RVHD1 and RVHD2)
- Myxomatosis

These diseases are fatal and vaccine-preventable. Please keep vaccinations up to date.

## Finding a rabbit-savvy vet

Not all vets are experienced with rabbits. Look for a vet with a specific interest in small mammals or exotic animals. The RWAF has a vet finder on their website.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
    {
      params: { slug: 'grooming-guide' },
      props: {
        article: {
          title: 'Grooming Your Rabbit',
          category: 'Grooming',
          readTime: '4 min read',
          emoji: '🪮',
          content: `
## How often?

**Short-haired breeds** (Dutch, Rex, Mini Lop): brush once a week, daily during moult seasons (spring and autumn).

**Long-haired breeds** (Lionhead, Angora, Cashmere Lop): daily brushing is necessary to prevent painful matting.

## Tools

- **Soft slicker brush**: good for most coats, removes loose fur gently
- **Fine-toothed comb**: for longer coats, works through any tangles
- **Flea comb**: useful during moults to remove loose undercoat
- **Nail clippers**: purpose-made small animal nail clippers — sharper and safer than human clippers

## Brushing technique

Work in the direction of fur growth. Use slow, gentle strokes. For long-haired breeds, work in sections and use the comb first to check for tangles before brushing.

Rabbits often enjoy grooming — it mimics what a bonded companion would do. Use it as bonding time.

## Nail clipping

Nails need trimming every 6–8 weeks. You'll see the clear tip extending beyond the pink quick (blood vessel). Clip the clear tip only.

If you're nervous or have a wriggly rabbit, we offer nail clipping as part of our boarding service, or as a standalone appointment. Many vets and rabbit-savvy groomers offer this too.

## What NOT to do

- **Never bathe a rabbit in water** — it causes severe stress and can lead to shock. Rabbits are clean animals that groom themselves.
- **Never use human or dog shampoos**
- **Don't try to cut out matted fur with scissors** — you can easily cut skin. Contact a vet or groomer for matting.
          `,
        },
      },
    },
  ];
}

const { article } = Astro.props;

const categoryColors: Record<string, string> = {
  Feeding: 'bg-orange-100 text-orange-700',
  Housing: 'bg-blue-100 text-blue-700',
  Bonding: 'bg-pink-100 text-pink-700',
  'First-time owners': 'bg-green-100 text-green-700',
  Health: 'bg-red-100 text-red-700',
  Grooming: 'bg-purple-100 text-purple-700',
};
---

<Base title={article.title} description={article.title}>

  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">

    <!-- Back -->
    <a href="/care" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm text-bunny-light hover:text-bunny-dark no-underline mb-8 transition-colors">
      ← All care guides
    </a>

    <!-- Header -->
    <div class="mb-8">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class={`text-xs font-medium px-3 py-1 rounded-full ${categoryColors[article.category] || 'bg-gray-100 text-gray-700'}`}>
          {article.category}
        </span>
        <span class="text-xs text-bunny-light">{article.readTime}</span>
      </div>
      <div class="text-6xl mb-4">{article.emoji}</div>
      <h1 class="font-lora text-3xl md:text-4xl font-semibold text-bunny-dark leading-tight">
        {article.title}
      </h1>
    </div>

    <!-- Content -->
    <div class="prose prose-bunny max-w-none" set:html={article.content.replace(/^## (.+)$/gm, '<h2>$1</h2>').replace(/^### (.+)$/gm, '<h3>$1</h3>').replace(/\*\*(.+?)\*\*/g, '<strong>$1</strong>').replace(/\*(.+?)\*/g, '<em>$1</em>').replace(/^- (.+)$/gm, '<li>$1</li>').replace(/(<li>[\s\S]*?<\/li>)/gm, (m) => `<ul class="my-3 space-y-1">${m}</ul>`)}>
    </div>

    <!-- CTA at end of article -->
    <div class="mt-12 pt-8 border-t border-tan bg-cream rounded-2xl p-6">
      <h3 class="font-lora font-semibold text-bunny-dark text-lg mb-2">
        Questions? We're happy to help.
      </h3>
      <p class="text-bunny-light text-sm mb-4">
        Even if you didn't buy your rabbit from us, feel free to get in touch. We love talking rabbits.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="/enquire" class="btn-primary text-sm">Ask us a question →</a>
        <a href="/care" class="btn-outline text-sm">More care guides</a>
      </div>
    </div>

  </article>

</Base>

